<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="99" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="99">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="99">
<taxonomicName authority="M.Roser &amp; H.R.Hamashaon Hagen, 2012" authorityName="Roeser &amp; H. R. Hamasha, Pl. Syst. Evol. 298 (365):" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="L." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Oloptum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Oloptum miliaceum" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="miliaceum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="99">Oloptum miliaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is native to Europe, particularly the whole Mediterranean region, from northern Africa, Sinai to Western Asia (Arabian Peninsula, Cyprus, Egypt, Iraq, Iran, Israel, Jordan, Lebanon, Palestinian territories, Syria, and Turkey) [
<bibRefCitation author="Freitag, H" journalOrPublisher="Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh" pageId="21" pageNumber="110" pagination="341 - 406" refId="B10" refString="Freitag, H, 1975. The genus Piptatherum (Gramineae) in Southwest Asia. Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh 33: 341 - 406" title="The genus Piptatherum (Gramineae) in Southwest Asia." volume="33" year="1975">Freitag 1975</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Soreng, RJ" journalOrPublisher="National Herbarium" pageId="22" pageNumber="111" pagination="1 - 730" publicationUrl="http://botany.si.edu/pubs/CUSNH/ContList.htm" refId="B30" refString="Soreng, RJ, Peterson, PM, Davidse, G, Judziewicz, EJ, Zuloaga, FO, Filgueiras, TS, Morrone, O, 2003. Catalogue of New World grasses (Poaceae): IV. subfamily Pooideae. Contributions from the U.S. National Herbarium 48: 1 - 730, http://botany.si.edu/pubs/CUSNH/ContList.htm" title="Catalogue of New World grasses (Poaceae): IV. subfamily Pooideae. Contributions from the U. S." url="http://botany.si.edu/pubs/CUSNH/ContList.htm" volume="48" year="2003">Soreng et al. 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5479/si.19382812.103" author="Ibrahim, KM" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Contributions to Botany" pageId="21" pageNumber="110" pagination="1 - 201" refId="B17" refString="Ibrahim, KM, Hosni, HA, Peterson, PM, 2016. Grasses of Egypt. Smithsonian Contributions to Botany 103: 1 - 201, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5479/si.19382812.103" title="Grasses of Egypt." url="https://doi.org/10.5479/si.19382812.103" volume="103" year="2016">Ibrahim et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
]. It is naturalized in southern Africa, Australia, New Zealand, North America (Arizona, California, Maryland) and South America (
<bibRefCitation author="Barkworth, ME" editor="Barkworth, ME" journalOrPublisher="Oxford Universtiy Press, New York" pageId="20" pageNumber="109" pagination="109 - 186" refId="B3" refString="Barkworth, ME, 2007. 10. Stipeae Dumort. In: Barkworth, ME, Capels, KM, Long, S, Anderton, LK, Piep, MB, Eds., Magnoliophyta: Commelinidae (in part): Poaceae, part 1. Oxford Universtiy Press, New York: 109 - 186" title="10. Stipeae Dumort." volumeTitle="Magnoliophyta: Commelinidae (in part): Poaceae, part 1." year="2007">Barkworth 2007</bibRefCitation>
), and has been cultivated in Mississippi, North Carolina, Tennessee, and Utah (see SEINet http://swbiodiversity.org/seinet/collections/list.php?db=all&amp;taxa=Achnatherum+miliaceum&amp;usethes=1&amp;taxontype=2&amp;page=1). The species occurs in various disturbed habitats along roadsides, ditches, borders of fields, dry river beds, and dumping grounds usually below 2000 m (
<bibRefCitation author="Freitag, H" journalOrPublisher="Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh" pageId="21" pageNumber="110" pagination="341 - 406" refId="B10" refString="Freitag, H, 1975. The genus Piptatherum (Gramineae) in Southwest Asia. Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh 33: 341 - 406" title="The genus Piptatherum (Gramineae) in Southwest Asia." volume="33" year="1975">Freitag 1975</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="100" pageId="10" pageNumber="99" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="99">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="100" pageId="10" pageNumber="99">
The unique morphological features of this taxon (glabrous lemma with a central vein not grooved, 3-veined glumes without transverse veinlets, and a callus with a circular disarticulation scar) were first recognized by 
<bibRefCitation author="Roshevitz, RJ" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="22" pageNumber="111" refId="B28" refString="Roshevitz, RJ, 1951. De genere Piptatherum P.B. notae criticae. Botanicheskie materialy Gerbariya Botanicheskogo Instituti imeni V. L. Komarova, Akademii Nauk SSSR (Leningrad) 14: 78-129." title="De genere Piptatherum P. B. notae criticae. Botanicheskie materialy Gerbariya Botanicheskogo Instituti imeni V. L. Komarova, Akademii Nauk SSSR (Leningrad) 14: 78 - 129." year="1951">Roshevitz (1951)</bibRefCitation>
and later officially named by 
<bibRefCitation author="Freitag, H" journalOrPublisher="Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh" pageId="21" pageNumber="110" pagination="341 - 406" refId="B10" refString="Freitag, H, 1975. The genus Piptatherum (Gramineae) in Southwest Asia. Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh 33: 341 - 406" title="The genus Piptatherum (Gramineae) in Southwest Asia." volume="33" year="1975">Freitag (1975)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Gramineae" genus="Piptatherum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Piptatherum subsp. sect." order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Miliacea" species="miliaceum" subSpecies="sect.">Piptatherum sect. Miliacea</taxonomicName>
Roshev. ex Freitag. Lemma epidermal pattern of 
<taxonomicName authority="M.Roser &amp; H.R.Hamashaon Hagen, 2012" authorityName="M.Roser &amp; H.R.Hamashaon Hagen" authorityYear="2012" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Oloptum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Oloptum" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="99">Oloptum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unusual among achnatheroid grasses resembling only that of 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Celtica" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Celtica" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="99">Celtica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is distinguished by having long fundamental cells irregularly alternating with silica bodies. In our earlier molecular analysis, 
<taxonomicName genus="O." lsidName="O. miliaceum" pageId="10" pageNumber="99" rank="species" species="miliaceum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="99">O. miliaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sister to the Eurasian 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Achnatherum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Achnatherum" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="99">Achnatherum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clade in the core 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Achnatherum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Achnatherum" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="99">Achnatherum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clade, which also 
<pageBreakToken pageId="11" pageNumber="100" start="start">includes</pageBreakToken>
<taxonomicName authorityName="M.Roser &amp; H.R.Hamasha" authorityYear="2012" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Stipellula" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Stipellula" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="100" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="100">Stipellula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S.W.L.Jacobs &amp; J.Everett" authorityYear="1996" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Austrostipa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Austrostipa" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="100" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="100">Austrostipa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
S.W.L. Jacobs &amp; J. Everett, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J.F.Veldkamp" authorityYear="1985" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Anemanthele" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Anemanthele" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="100" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="100">Anemanthele</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Veldkamp and 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Celtica" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Celtica" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="100" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="100">Celtica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
F.M. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Vázquez">Vazquez</normalizedToken>
&amp; Barkworth (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.606015" author="Romaschenko, K" journalOrPublisher="Aarhus University Press, Denmark" pageId="22" pageNumber="111" refId="B25" refString="Romaschenko, K, Peterson, PM, Soreng, RJ, Futorna, O, Susanna, A, 2011. Phylogenetics of Piptatherum s.l. (Poaceae: Stipeae): Evidence for a new genus, Piptatheropsis, and resurrection of Patis. Taxon 60(6): 1703-1716. https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.606015" title="Phylogenetics of Piptatherum s. l. (Poaceae: Stipeae): Evidence for a new genus, Piptatheropsis, and resurrection of Patis. Taxon 60 (6): 1703 - 1716." url="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.606015" year="2011">Romaschenko et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.611002" author="Romaschenko, K" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="22" pageNumber="111" pagination="18 - 44" refId="B26" refString="Romaschenko, K, Peterson, PM, Soreng, RJ, Garcia-Jacas, N, Futorna, O, Susanna, A, 2012. Systematics and evolution of the needle grasses (Poaceae: Pooideae: Stipeae) based on analysis of multiple chloroplast loci, ITS, and lemma micromorphology. Taxon 61 (1): 18 - 44, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.611002" title="Systematics and evolution of the needle grasses (Poaceae: Pooideae: Stipeae) based on analysis of multiple chloroplast loci, ITS, and lemma micromorphology." url="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.611002" volume="61" year="2012">2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="100">
Traditionally, two subspecies have been recognized. 
<taxonomicName authority="M.Roser &amp; H.R.Hamashaon Hagen, 2012" authorityName="M.Roser &amp; H.R.Hamashaon Hagen" authorityYear="2012" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Oloptum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Oloptum miliaceum subsp. thomasii" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="100" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="miliaceum" subSpecies="thomasii">Oloptum miliaceum subsp. thomasii</taxonomicName>
(Duby) Boiss. differs from the typical form in having densely verticillate panicles with 15-30 or more often sterile branches on the lowest whorl (
<bibRefCitation author="Freitag, H" journalOrPublisher="Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh" pageId="21" pageNumber="110" pagination="341 - 406" refId="B10" refString="Freitag, H, 1975. The genus Piptatherum (Gramineae) in Southwest Asia. Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh 33: 341 - 406" title="The genus Piptatherum (Gramineae) in Southwest Asia." volume="33" year="1975">Freitag 1975</bibRefCitation>
). There is genetic variation between these two subspecies in our earlier analyses (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.606015" author="Romaschenko, K" journalOrPublisher="Aarhus University Press, Denmark" pageId="22" pageNumber="111" refId="B25" refString="Romaschenko, K, Peterson, PM, Soreng, RJ, Futorna, O, Susanna, A, 2011. Phylogenetics of Piptatherum s.l. (Poaceae: Stipeae): Evidence for a new genus, Piptatheropsis, and resurrection of Patis. Taxon 60(6): 1703-1716. https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.606015" title="Phylogenetics of Piptatherum s. l. (Poaceae: Stipeae): Evidence for a new genus, Piptatheropsis, and resurrection of Patis. Taxon 60 (6): 1703 - 1716." url="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.606015" year="2011">Romaschenko et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.611002" author="Romaschenko, K" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="22" pageNumber="111" pagination="18 - 44" refId="B26" refString="Romaschenko, K, Peterson, PM, Soreng, RJ, Garcia-Jacas, N, Futorna, O, Susanna, A, 2012. Systematics and evolution of the needle grasses (Poaceae: Pooideae: Stipeae) based on analysis of multiple chloroplast loci, ITS, and lemma micromorphology. Taxon 61 (1): 18 - 44, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.611002" title="Systematics and evolution of the needle grasses (Poaceae: Pooideae: Stipeae) based on analysis of multiple chloroplast loci, ITS, and lemma micromorphology." url="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.611002" volume="61" year="2012">2012</bibRefCitation>
). A molecular study with a larger sample of the subspecies is necessary to fully explore evolutionary relationships.
</paragraph>
